<Author>jeffriesPoole
<Content>A families HK review We stayed at the Ramada for 12 nights, having two rooms for our family of five. From the airport we took a designated luxury hotel to hotel coach, which we booked once we had got off the plane. Guides showed us where to wait and then directed us onto the right coach it took about 35 minutes and we paid 拢42 return for the 5 of us. On our return the consiege phoned through our request for pick-up and we were the only ones on it!!!The rooms were spacious, clean and even had sea views. The staff were really helpful and we would definitely recommend this hotel to others.  As already stated by another user, across the road was a 24hr 'circle K', and just 2 minutes down from it towards Kennedy town was a great laundarette, (The Great China Laundry Shop) very cheap and in that heat/humidity very welcome.We took the tram each day into central and then depending on where we went, either the MTR, buses or Star Ferry. With regard to the Star Ferry after inquiring how much extra it was to ride on the top deck, we felt the extra 3p was well worth it!!!!! especially with Starbucks coffee and an unmissable wafflle shop to tempt you whilst waiting. R66 the revolving restaurant at the Hopewell Centre, Wan Chai was great the afternoon tea buffet was only HK$80 a head. The local markets nearby were very reasonably priced also.The 'Fa Yuen Street Market' in Mongkok was good value and seemed to be where the local bargain hunters shopped. We purchased a museum pass for HK$30 each which covered about 9 museums and lasted for 7 days, great to escape the heat and/or rain!!Taking the mid-level escalators on Hong Kong Island, near Jubilee Street was fun especially as we found Subway and Krispy-Kreme.If you want some good views of the city for free, 2 IFC and Bank of China both have viewing galleries, just take some photo ID.Swimming in the outdoor pools at Victoria Park was a favourite and cost no more than HK$19 (adult) each for 3 hour sessions.Hong Kong park was a real bonus, stop at 'Olivers sandwich bar' in the basement of Citibank Plaza, which you have to walk through for a cheap picnic.Kowloon Park especially on Sunday between 2.30pm and 4pm at Kung Fu corner was entertaining, and just to people watch.Afternoon tea at the Peninsular especially if you are a James Bond fan, was expensive HK$248 but for nostalgia and sheer indulgence a must.Overall the transportation was excellent, cheap and easy to get around. At no time did we feel unsafe whilst walking around late at night, in fact locals were helpful and polite.These were some of our highlights not withstanding the obvious the Peak, Disneyland, Ocean Park and Nyong Ping, which are still all worth a visit.For free internet access use McCafe and Pacific Coffee Company. 
