<Author>ju123
<Content>An absolute gem of a hotel.... We had 5 nights in Hong Kong as part of a 7 month round the world trip and opted for the Ramada on HK Island as opposed to staying in Kowloon. I must admit the price was the main reason as it seemed much cheaper than a lot of the other HK hotels, but from the web pictures it looked modern and although the location wasn't quite right we were looking forward to the stay.Check in was tough. There was a trainee working on the desk and her English was non existent, fortunately there was another girl on hand to assist and despite a few teething problems with credit card guarantees we were checked in smoothly and headed to our room.One really nice touch about the hotel was the hotel porter would always push the lift button when he saw you approaching, so in most instances the lifts were ready once you got there. It's these little small things that make a hotel.Anyway to the room. We had read previously about single guests being upgraded to a suite room, which consisted of 3 parts. Firstly the entrance and bathroom area, then a living room type section, followed by the bedroom. We didn't expect to get a room like this as we had only paid for a standard room, so we were very surprised to find we were allocated a suite room. It was a magnificent room, very modern and bright with good air conditioning. A real joy to spend 5 nights in there in all honesty.The rest of the hotel is also very nice and modern. A special word also for the concierge, who was very helpful with local information and travel instructions.As for location, well we absolutely loved it. Sure it is away from the main downtown area, and obviously across the river from Kowloon but this felt like real Hong Kong. It was about a 20min walk to the underground station, although countless trams came back and forth and stopped right outside the hotel, all for a cost of 2HKD...about 14p in sterling. We were always greeted with a smile by the locals and loved the views from the top of the trams. It was a little slower in the evenings to get around, but if you haven't got to rush anywhere then it is the best way to get around. Taxis were very cheap also.As I said the walk to the first stop on the underground is about 20mins, but it is down the dried fish road which in itself is a tourist attraction, if a little smelly.One final thing that really helped us is the laundry. Don't use the hotel service, instead cross the road directly in front of the hotel and walk left. About a minutes walk is a lovely local laundry where the owners did a huge bag of washing for 16HKD, plus she always gave us 20% discount. Laundry was always ready to pick up before 6pm that evening. Fantastic.All in all I would recommend this hotel to everybody. It's in a great different location with good transport links. As for the room, it was 2nd only to the Novotel HK airport for quality during our whole 7 months trip. 
