<Content>Decent overnight choice in Hong Kong We overnighted here on the night of August 5th, just at the tailend of the typhoon that paralysed the HK airport. Our Cathay flight was delayed 4 hours and we arrived at the hotel at 00:30, just after midnight. To our surprise there were still some other guests checking in, probably got delayed on the way in too. We were upgraded to their suite as it seems to be the policy for any singles or couples who did not require 2 beds since there appears to be more of these suites than regular twin bedded rooms. Everything about these rooms were said in the other reviews so I will not go into details here, just the typical deluxe room with the divided living room and bedroom, and you cannot see the TV from your bed, a major pet peeve of many but we did not make use of the TV since we went straight to the shower and bed.Room: The room is very well finished and spotlessly clean, we were assigned on the 27th floor, at first we thought it was a smoking floor since only 15 and 25 were marked with a non-smoking sign on the elevator, but the room's door had a non-smoking sign on it and we did not smell any smoke so it was all good. The double bed was very hard, like most Asian hotels, but we were too exhausted to care after a 13 hour flight and a12 hour layover at Vancouver.Washroom: The toilet only flush when you hold the button all the way down for the entire duration of the flush, very annoying and thankfully we're only staying overnight. The shower stall is also extremely tight and small for anyone over 5'9 (I'm 6'0). It appears that this hotel serves a largely mainland Chinese demographic so I guess this explains the small size of the shower. Checking out: Since it was a Sunday the shuttle bus to the pier did not run, bummer. But the bellboy was very nice and helped us load our luggage onto a Taxi he grabbed for us while we were checking out. Funny blooper: The cabbie asked us where to? in Mandarin as he first thought we were from 